,Recommended,520010,32729670,Posted: 24 June,all,Ganerumo,"Climbey is a fun if perfectible VR experience which, while a good introduction to more eccentric methods of locomotion, is lacking in content.GRAPHICSBy far not the game's strongest suit, Climbey has no art style to speak of. The minimalistic, purposefully WIP design is appreciable for how readable it makes each level, but the drawback is that the game is not particularly pretty or interesting to look at.GAMEPLAYClimbey's whole premise is in its name: you climb. That's really all there is to it. Locomotion is both based on arm-swinging and dragging yourself along surfaces onto which you can hold, with one or both hands. The player's interaction with each surface is simple enough: white blocks can be grabbed, grey blocks cannot, blue (ice) blocks are slippery and red (lava) blocks kill on impact.Past this, the game's fun factor entirely revolves around the levels themselves, which sadly aren't all good. The stock array of levels can be quite forgettable and often offer a single, fairly simple challenge based on one gimmick which varies every time. While user-created levels are often more daring and complex, if only for their attempts at being thematic (as much as the game's artstyle allows them, really), they are often extremely linear.Another issue of gameplay is the jumping. It is possible to leap across relatively short distances (albeit still far exceeding the average human ability) by grabbing onto the air and pulling back. While timing helps, the actual results is still mostly random and only becomes more difficult to control over longer jumps - and a dangerously high amount of levels rely heavily on jumping across particularly long distances. This creates a big problem especially when the player has to jump backwards or while holding onto objects, dozens of meters above the nearest surface. Community-made levels in particular over-utilize long distance jumps to the point of being infuriating.VR IMPLEMENTATIONClimbey in its current form would not be playable without VR. Motion-tracked hands is integral to gameplay but room-scale is relatively unneeded: due to the rather physical nature of the game it is obviously better to stand up clear of any other objects, but it is possible to play the entire game without ever moving your legs. The option to enable 90° turning via the touchpads also makes it possible to play entirely still without turning around, especially useful if you are confined to a 180° playspace.The game is relatively high on the discomfort scale: the lack of touchpad locomotion (arguably the most prone to causing simulation sickness) in favor of dragging/armswinging is rather comfortable in itself, but the game has a lot of forced movement in the form of slippery platforms, ziplines, trampolines and of course plenty of falling down. The sense of vertigo is also very prominent for obvious reasons and while the game does not pretend to be a cure for a fear of heights, enough time spent toying around with it will greatly dull the effect."
,Recommended,520010,32657014,Posted: 22 June,all,The Hellmare,"You remember those Assassin's Creed games you all have tried atleast once in your life? Climbing up monsterous towers and climbing window to window doing some really sick parkour throughout the city. Yeah, this is like that. With a strong community of builders on the workshop this game never seems to disappoint whenever I launch it. You're running, jumping, extending your arm as far as it can reach, and taking the leap of faith in every new level you play. You can take it easy or take on the hardest challenges made. This game can fit anyone's level of skill and it retains its fun every time you play. Surely a game on my top 5 list of VR games."
